00:03:17.350 --> 00:03:21.560
But the sort of 101
version is this.

00:03:21.560 --> 00:03:26.050
About every 50 years, the
societal business model

00:03:26.050 --> 00:03:28.360
hits a buffer, hits a problem.

00:03:28.360 --> 00:03:32.300
And what we tend to observe
is a fairly rapid mutation

00:03:32.300 --> 00:03:33.280
of a system.

00:03:33.280 --> 00:03:36.390
New social institutions,
new mixture of industry,

00:03:36.390 --> 00:03:40.720
finance, services, consumption.

00:03:40.720 --> 00:03:45.970
The classic one is in the 1840s
where the railways arrived

00:03:45.970 --> 00:03:49.380
to take over from an initial
spurt of development that

00:03:49.380 --> 00:03:51.570
was fueled by the rise
of the factory system

00:03:51.570 --> 00:03:53.110
alongside canals.

00:03:53.110 --> 00:03:54.270
You get railways.

00:03:54.270 --> 00:03:56.400
And then in the
1890s, you get what

00:03:56.400 --> 00:03:59.150
we call the second Industrial
Revolution, this fusion

00:03:59.150 --> 00:04:03.660
of electrical engineering,
of material science,

00:04:03.660 --> 00:04:07.010
of big infrastructure.

00:04:07.010 --> 00:04:08.640
Iron is replaced by steel.

00:04:08.640 --> 00:04:11.270
The telegraph is
replaced by telephones,

00:04:11.270 --> 00:04:12.820
et cetera, et cetera.

00:04:12.820 --> 00:04:15.240
And then in World War II, we
get this other adaptation,

00:04:15.240 --> 00:04:17.990
this huge synthesis of
new-- a new synthesis

00:04:17.990 --> 00:04:21.079
between technology,
consumption, et cetera.

00:04:21.079 --> 00:04:23.080
One of the things
we observe when

00:04:23.080 --> 00:04:26.670
we look at social historians,
at these moments of mutation

00:04:26.670 --> 00:04:30.240
and big change in capitalism,
is that there's nearly always,

00:04:30.240 --> 00:04:33.120
when something goes wrong,
the knee-jerk reaction

00:04:33.120 --> 00:04:35.730
is nearly always for the
elite to try and solve it

00:04:35.730 --> 00:04:38.910
through pressure on wages,
pressure on consumption.

00:04:38.910 --> 00:04:41.980
Basically just cuts everybody's
wages and carry on as normal.

00:04:41.980 --> 00:04:44.290
And usually, up to
now what's happened

00:04:44.290 --> 00:04:49.900
is that that hasn't worked
because workers resisted.

00:04:49.900 --> 00:04:52.190
The 1880s and '90s are
a brilliant example

00:04:52.190 --> 00:04:55.830
of this from social history.

00:04:55.830 --> 00:04:59.580
But this time, it didn't happen
because the specific solution

00:04:59.580 --> 00:05:03.330
that was adopted when the
old Keynesian economics

00:05:03.330 --> 00:05:08.610
of the 1970s and '80s fell apart
was what we call neoliberalism.

00:05:08.610 --> 00:05:12.540
That is, a free market system
in which wages were more or less

00:05:12.540 --> 00:05:14.210
strategically suppressed.

00:05:14.210 --> 00:05:16.360
So any Americans
here may know that

00:05:16.360 --> 00:05:21.910
the median hourly male wage in
America was the same in 2008

00:05:21.910 --> 00:05:24.200
as it was in 1973.

00:05:24.200 --> 00:05:30.380
So lower was much worse,
higher was much better.

00:05:30.380 --> 00:05:32.890
And this is a problem,
because it means--

00:05:32.890 --> 00:05:36.782
and this is the kind
of clue number one

00:05:36.782 --> 00:05:39.060
why we might be
facing strategic,

00:05:39.060 --> 00:05:43.280
big 200-year long kind
of epochal change--

00:05:43.280 --> 00:05:47.850
is that if you get a situation
where capitalism is in trouble

00:05:47.850 --> 00:05:51.040
and it adapts through
suppressing wages,

00:05:51.040 --> 00:05:53.720
then what it
eventually does is it

00:05:53.720 --> 00:05:55.640
finds another solution
to consumption,

00:05:55.640 --> 00:05:56.690
and that is credit.

00:05:56.690 --> 00:05:59.690
So since about the 1990s,
we have a situation

00:05:59.690 --> 00:06:02.780
where wages are suppressed
for the mass of people,

00:06:02.780 --> 00:06:07.150
and yet credit is very,
very much more available

00:06:07.150 --> 00:06:08.140
than it ever was.

00:06:08.140 --> 00:06:10.312
What happens there
is it's almost

00:06:10.312 --> 00:06:12.770
like a law of physics, some of
your physicians in the room.

00:06:12.770 --> 00:06:15.030
That laws of physics,
but it's economic,

00:06:15.030 --> 00:06:18.150
that if you've got static
incomes and ever-expanding

00:06:18.150 --> 00:06:20.780
credit, that at some point,
the kind of wine collections

00:06:20.780 --> 00:06:23.740
and the art collections and the
luxury apartments at Vauxhall

00:06:23.740 --> 00:06:27.300
Bridge cannot go on rising in
value, and they just snap back.

00:06:27.300 --> 00:06:28.940
We call that a boom-bust cycle.

00:06:28.940 --> 00:06:32.250
And we've lived through
three in 15 years.

00:06:32.250 --> 00:06:33.830
So this is a signal
that something

00:06:33.830 --> 00:06:35.990
might be wrong with
the economics that

00:06:35.990 --> 00:06:38.870
is not being actually
solved by the technology.

00:06:38.870 --> 00:06:42.200
It's not being solved by the
creation of new, high value,

00:06:42.200 --> 00:06:47.820
high wage, high sort
of well being synthesis

00:06:47.820 --> 00:06:52.760
of the kind you got in the 10
to 15 years before World War I.

00:06:52.760 --> 00:06:54.540
OK.

00:06:54.540 --> 00:07:00.090
Now here's my explanation,
drawn on the work of others,

00:07:00.090 --> 00:07:02.920
of why that might be happening.

00:07:02.920 --> 00:07:07.010
Because information technology
is different in the three

00:07:07.010 --> 00:07:09.500
following ways.

00:07:09.500 --> 00:07:14.050
First of all, it is corroding
the price mechanism.

00:07:14.050 --> 00:07:17.020
An economist call
Paul Romer in 1990

00:07:17.020 --> 00:07:21.150
wrote a paper that has gone
down in history for its title,

00:07:21.150 --> 00:07:23.040
because a British
politician Ed [INAUDIBLE]

00:07:23.040 --> 00:07:24.690
once tried to quote
it in Parliament.

00:07:24.690 --> 00:07:27.580
It's called "Endogenous
Technological Change."

00:07:27.580 --> 00:07:30.930
But the 101 warm
version of it is

00:07:30.930 --> 00:07:35.255
that if you can-- if the
reproduction cost of something

00:07:35.255 --> 00:07:40.790
is dictated by the actions
Command-C, Command-V,

00:07:40.790 --> 00:07:44.210
then economics tells you that
its price should fall to zero,

00:07:44.210 --> 00:07:45.520
or close to zero.

00:07:45.520 --> 00:07:48.420
Because you're using zero
energy, or almost no energy,

00:07:48.420 --> 00:07:51.097
almost no labor, and
almost no materials.

00:07:51.097 --> 00:07:53.180
We'll come to how much
material, energy, and labor

00:07:53.180 --> 00:07:54.410
you're using in a minute.

00:07:54.410 --> 00:07:59.180
But if you can copy something
for free, then economics,

00:07:59.180 --> 00:08:01.860
mainstream, non-market,
Marxist economics

00:08:01.860 --> 00:08:03.960
tells you that
its price is going

00:08:03.960 --> 00:08:07.480
to be close to zero under
conditions of competition.

00:08:07.480 --> 00:08:08.750
This is what Romer says.

00:08:08.750 --> 00:08:11.280
Also about information
goods is they are

00:08:11.280 --> 00:08:13.370
what economists call non-rival.

00:08:13.370 --> 00:08:15.540
So if you smoke one
inch of a cigarette,

00:08:15.540 --> 00:08:17.280
I can't smoke that one inch.

00:08:17.280 --> 00:08:19.020
I can smoke the next
inch, especially

00:08:19.020 --> 00:08:22.830
if it's one of those
cigarettes that you share.

00:08:22.830 --> 00:08:24.540
But I can't smoke
the same inch as you.

00:08:24.540 --> 00:08:25.930
It's a rival good.

00:08:25.930 --> 00:08:28.040
Not true of an MP3 track.

00:08:28.040 --> 00:08:34.110
Not true of the database
that builds a Boeing 787.

00:08:34.110 --> 00:08:39.130
You can copy it and use it at
the exact same time for free.

00:08:39.130 --> 00:08:43.850
Now Romer said in this
situation, the only thing that

00:08:43.850 --> 00:08:45.540
keeps the price
mechanism-- i.e.,

00:08:45.540 --> 00:08:50.180
things cost more than zero--
is if you artificially

00:08:50.180 --> 00:08:52.120
create scarcity.

00:08:52.120 --> 00:08:54.060
Because information
is now abundant.

00:08:54.060 --> 00:08:56.610
It's unlike all other goods.

00:08:56.610 --> 00:08:58.130
Obviously, there
are limits to it.

00:08:58.130 --> 00:09:00.010
The limits are
storage and bandwidth.

00:09:00.010 --> 00:09:03.170
But information is
essentially abundant, as far

00:09:03.170 --> 00:09:04.860
as most people are concerned.

00:09:04.860 --> 00:09:07.630
And so what you do to
maintain any kind of price

00:09:07.630 --> 00:09:10.990
is you create artificial
restrictions on it,

00:09:10.990 --> 00:09:12.830
using either a widget.

00:09:12.830 --> 00:09:14.150
You remember DVDs.

00:09:14.150 --> 00:09:15.870
You couldn't copy
a DVD because there

00:09:15.870 --> 00:09:18.810
was a widget inside the
protected software that

00:09:18.810 --> 00:09:22.150
takes 13-year-olds about
10 seconds to break,

00:09:22.150 --> 00:09:23.820
but nevertheless, it's there.

00:09:23.820 --> 00:09:25.900
Or you get a good
lawyer, and you

00:09:25.900 --> 00:09:27.780
arrest every person
in the car park

00:09:27.780 --> 00:09:30.370
at the supermarket going
around with fake DVDs,

00:09:30.370 --> 00:09:32.990
and you sue the pants off
everybody who tries to copy.

00:09:32.990 --> 00:09:34.780
You'd shut down
BitTorrent, and et cetera,

00:09:34.780 --> 00:09:37.570
et cetera, et cetera.

00:09:37.570 --> 00:09:40.380
Now you can do that.

00:09:40.380 --> 00:09:46.010
But essentially, the good
itself is replicable for free.

00:09:46.010 --> 00:09:48.622
The next thing
information does--

00:09:48.622 --> 00:09:50.330
and you will be very,
very aware of this.

00:09:50.330 --> 00:09:52.490
Some of the audiences I
speak to are just, oh, wow.

00:09:52.490 --> 00:09:52.990
Is it?

00:09:52.990 --> 00:09:56.440
But information dealings
work from wages.

00:09:56.440 --> 00:09:58.470
Information blurs
the distinction

00:09:58.470 --> 00:10:02.750
between work and non-work,
or what we used to call life.

00:10:02.750 --> 00:10:08.850
And it de-links work
hours from wages.

00:10:08.850 --> 00:10:11.130
So my dad's generation,
they turn up at a factory.

00:10:11.130 --> 00:10:13.040
If you're not there
on the production line

00:10:13.040 --> 00:10:16.022
cranking the screw here, I
can't tweak the nut here.

00:10:16.022 --> 00:10:17.980
So you and me have to
turn up at the same time,

00:10:17.980 --> 00:10:19.105
and the work is sequential.

00:10:19.105 --> 00:10:19.850
It goes past.

00:10:19.850 --> 00:10:21.890
Best to give us both
a little card, clock

00:10:21.890 --> 00:10:24.345
into a machine that
goes clunk, and pay

00:10:24.345 --> 00:10:27.360
is when we arrive, and stop
paying us when we leave.

00:10:27.360 --> 00:10:30.200
That's work-- that's
capitalist work.

00:10:30.200 --> 00:10:31.285
Your work is different.

00:10:31.285 --> 00:10:33.910
I mean, when I tell people about
the white board and the yellow

00:10:33.910 --> 00:10:36.430
Post-it notes who are not
in the world you're in, they

00:10:36.430 --> 00:10:37.990
don't-- they go, wow, really?

00:10:37.990 --> 00:10:39.200
Do people work like that?

00:10:39.200 --> 00:10:43.262
But you will know the modular
basis of most information work.

00:10:43.262 --> 00:10:44.720
You pick up the
bit of the project,

00:10:44.720 --> 00:10:47.265
you work with it for a bit,
you put the Post-it note back

00:10:47.265 --> 00:10:48.630
and you record your work.

00:10:48.630 --> 00:10:50.400
Somebody else can
take it, pick it up.

00:10:50.400 --> 00:10:54.970
Modular work allows very,
very easily distributed

00:10:54.970 --> 00:10:58.090
and networked forms
of organization.

00:10:58.090 --> 00:11:02.030
But it really challenges,
what are we being paid for?

00:11:02.030 --> 00:11:04.020
So my common experience
like some of you

00:11:04.020 --> 00:11:05.860
is you get on a
plane to Brussels,

00:11:05.860 --> 00:11:08.010
you try and keep your
elbows away from the person

00:11:08.010 --> 00:11:10.280
next to you, you try
and do a bit of work.

00:11:10.280 --> 00:11:12.590
If it was a factory,
it would be closed down

00:11:12.590 --> 00:11:15.900
on health and safety grounds,
the kind of morning flight

00:11:15.900 --> 00:11:16.550
to Brussels.

00:11:16.550 --> 00:11:18.740
But we are actually all working.

00:11:18.740 --> 00:11:21.040
Nobody asked us, what
time did you start work?

00:11:21.040 --> 00:11:23.040
Nobody really cares if
I flip to the latest

00:11:23.040 --> 00:11:24.520
episode of "Game
of Thrones" when

00:11:24.520 --> 00:11:26.090
I get sick of my spreadsheet.

00:11:26.090 --> 00:11:29.190
Because we work at a
target, not to time.

00:11:29.190 --> 00:11:32.200
And that in itself
is quite interesting,

00:11:32.200 --> 00:11:34.100
because it means at
the higher level,

00:11:34.100 --> 00:11:36.710
we're all target-based
rather than time-based.

00:11:36.710 --> 00:11:38.270
And at the lower
level, we're tending

00:11:38.270 --> 00:11:41.210
to create jobs in a
lot of societies that

00:11:41.210 --> 00:11:43.090
almost don't need to exist.

00:11:43.090 --> 00:11:46.890
We could be automating a
lot of work a lot faster,

00:11:46.890 --> 00:11:49.340
but the societal
limits to it, our fear

00:11:49.340 --> 00:11:54.850
of creating-- the Oxford Martin
Institute says 47% of all jobs

00:11:54.850 --> 00:11:59.050
are automatable within 30
years-- our fear of doing it

00:11:59.050 --> 00:12:01.090
means we don't do
it, and we instead

00:12:01.090 --> 00:12:03.640
create lots of
person-to-person jobs

00:12:03.640 --> 00:12:08.432
at very, very low value that
probably don't need to exist.

00:12:08.432 --> 00:12:10.390
The first time I walked
into a McDonald's where

00:12:10.390 --> 00:12:14.210
you could touch screen and undo
your order on a touch screen

00:12:14.210 --> 00:12:18.186
and then swipe your
card, I mentally cheered.

00:12:18.186 --> 00:12:20.760
Because it's no fun
being one of those people

00:12:20.760 --> 00:12:21.890
behind the counter.

00:12:21.890 --> 00:12:23.690
It's no fun standing
in the queues going,

00:12:23.690 --> 00:12:25.670
am I being served
or not being served?

00:12:25.670 --> 00:12:27.860
Is she serving me or not?

00:12:27.860 --> 00:12:29.820
The whole thing is automatable.

00:12:29.820 --> 00:12:31.730
Who knew?

