When I first got a
car, we used to put it

00:12:33.915 --> 00:12:36.690
in something called a car wash.

00:12:36.690 --> 00:12:37.750
It was a machine.

00:12:37.750 --> 00:12:40.685
You know, you put your coin
in and the thing came over you

00:12:40.685 --> 00:12:41.960
and washed your car.

00:12:41.960 --> 00:12:43.980
Who knew that eight
guys with rags

00:12:43.980 --> 00:12:46.050
could undercut that machine?

00:12:46.050 --> 00:12:49.130
They undercut it because
labor is so cheap.

00:12:49.130 --> 00:12:52.482
In other words, we're
not forced to innovate.

00:12:52.482 --> 00:12:53.850
So that's the second thing.

00:12:53.850 --> 00:12:54.950
Work and wages.

00:12:54.950 --> 00:12:57.400
And the third thing that
flows on from the modularity

00:12:57.400 --> 00:13:00.790
is that organizations and
hierarchies and ownerships

00:13:00.790 --> 00:13:03.230
are beginning to
fragment as well.

00:13:03.230 --> 00:13:06.220
So you know that many
people in your space,

00:13:06.220 --> 00:13:08.960
also in the open source
space, will literally

00:13:08.960 --> 00:13:13.390
be working in no managed--
no managed hierarchies.

00:13:13.390 --> 00:13:15.500
They'll be working in
very flat hierarchies.

00:13:15.500 --> 00:13:17.540
They'll be working
sometimes non-managed.

00:13:17.540 --> 00:13:20.210
And in some
organizations, the product

00:13:20.210 --> 00:13:22.480
is produced in a
non-managed way.

00:13:22.480 --> 00:13:25.210
Wikipedia is a great
example, because nobody

00:13:25.210 --> 00:13:28.320
tells some professor
sitting in Seattle

00:13:28.320 --> 00:13:31.350
or wherever to do a
page about Napoleon.

00:13:31.350 --> 00:13:32.570
They just do it.

00:13:32.570 --> 00:13:36.010
The organization facilitates
the voluntary creation

00:13:36.010 --> 00:13:37.610
of a product.

00:13:37.610 --> 00:13:39.050
But you can see,
those of you who

00:13:39.050 --> 00:13:42.470
use open source tools
will know that, in fact,

00:13:42.470 --> 00:13:44.770
that way of working,
it's not like somebody

00:13:44.770 --> 00:13:47.650
sitting in the middle
of a committee.

00:13:47.650 --> 00:13:50.200
There is a committee
on TCP/IP isn't there?

00:13:50.200 --> 00:13:51.910
There's a committee
that looks after it.

00:13:51.910 --> 00:13:54.810
But that committee doesn't
tell people how to improve it.

00:13:54.810 --> 00:13:56.940
It just improves itself
through interaction

00:13:56.940 --> 00:13:59.520
of people who use it and
make improvements to it.

00:13:59.520 --> 00:14:01.280
Ruby on Rails, et cetera.

00:14:01.280 --> 00:14:05.780
So these three things, the
price mechanism dissolving,

00:14:05.780 --> 00:14:08.080
the link between work
and wages dissolving,

00:14:08.080 --> 00:14:11.300
and then organizations and
hierarchies-- organizations

00:14:11.300 --> 00:14:14.200
and hierarchies being
decentralized, falling apart,

00:14:14.200 --> 00:14:16.930
and the ownership of
things not being clear.

00:14:16.930 --> 00:14:20.320
So who owns Wikipedia?

00:14:20.320 --> 00:14:23.060
Well, you know, technically
probably Jimmy Wales probably

00:14:23.060 --> 00:14:23.880
owns it.

00:14:23.880 --> 00:14:25.970
But it is an open source
product with which

00:14:25.970 --> 00:14:27.700
every other
corporation on Earth,

00:14:27.700 --> 00:14:31.090
if you trace their IP addresses,
transacts every day, probably

00:14:31.090 --> 00:14:33.350
every minute.

00:14:33.350 --> 00:14:37.090
This is very new in the
history of capitalism.

00:14:37.090 --> 00:14:40.920
So the price fall thing is
the most important thing.

00:14:40.920 --> 00:14:41.430
Why?

00:14:41.430 --> 00:14:44.890
Because it doesn't
just impact on-- it

00:14:44.890 --> 00:14:47.800
doesn't just impact
on information goods,

00:14:47.800 --> 00:14:50.530
on virtual things.

00:14:50.530 --> 00:14:54.010
I kind of rebel against the word
cyber, immaterial, and virtual.

00:14:54.010 --> 00:14:57.810
Because as the Oxford
professor of philosophy,

00:14:57.810 --> 00:15:01.452
Luciano Floridi tells us,
information is physical.

00:15:01.452 --> 00:15:03.160
Those of use who have
studied cybernetics

00:15:03.160 --> 00:15:07.580
know about Norbert Wiener, the
founder of cybernetics in 1948

00:15:07.580 --> 00:15:11.795
writes, "information is
neither mass nor energy."

00:15:11.795 --> 00:15:14.290
It is something
new, and materialism

00:15:14.290 --> 00:15:16.860
has to adjust for that.

00:15:16.860 --> 00:15:19.820
I disagree with that,
and Floridi does as well.

00:15:19.820 --> 00:15:22.320
I say information
has its own dynamic

00:15:22.320 --> 00:15:23.820
separate to mass and energy.

00:15:23.820 --> 00:15:27.660
Of course, funnily enough,
the laws of that dynamic

00:15:27.660 --> 00:15:33.810
are weirdly mappable onto
the laws of thermodynamics.

00:15:33.810 --> 00:15:35.580
But leave that aside.

00:15:35.580 --> 00:15:38.550
But it needs mass and
energy for representation.

00:15:38.550 --> 00:15:40.960
And therefore, it exists
in the physical world.

00:15:40.960 --> 00:15:44.060
And that's what explains
any physical good that

00:15:44.060 --> 00:15:46.770
is heavily dependent on
an information content

00:15:46.770 --> 00:15:50.630
is also very susceptible to
this exponential price fall that

00:15:50.630 --> 00:15:53.770
is inherent in the idea of
information costs nothing

00:15:53.770 --> 00:15:54.870
to reproduce.

00:15:54.870 --> 00:15:57.360
So you will know that
if I add PowerPoint,

00:15:57.360 --> 00:16:00.620
the price of bandwidth,
processing power, and storage

00:16:00.620 --> 00:16:03.190
is all over a 15-year
period exponentially

00:16:03.190 --> 00:16:05.190
off a cliff like that.

00:16:05.190 --> 00:16:07.907
Deloitte, the
consultancy, believes--

00:16:07.907 --> 00:16:09.740
I don't know whether
this is true-- believes

00:16:09.740 --> 00:16:11.970
that that exponentially
will just carry on.

00:16:11.970 --> 00:16:13.937
They call them
exponential technologies.

00:16:13.937 --> 00:16:15.770
And it means that we've
never lived through.

00:16:15.770 --> 00:16:18.290
My dad's generation, my
granddad's generation,

00:16:18.290 --> 00:16:21.930
industrial workers in factories
never lived through a period

00:16:21.930 --> 00:16:25.100
when a technology fell off
a cliff in price terms.

00:16:25.100 --> 00:16:27.530
And how do we know
that it's important?

00:16:27.530 --> 00:16:30.870
Because it's also affecting
things like DNA sequencing.

00:16:30.870 --> 00:16:34.620
The exponential curve of
DNA sequencing price fall

00:16:34.620 --> 00:16:36.610
is faster than Moore's law.

00:16:36.610 --> 00:16:38.660
It's actually,
bang, off a cliff.

00:16:38.660 --> 00:16:40.840
If you thought your kids
would make a big living,

00:16:40.840 --> 00:16:45.989
a high value living sequencing
DNA, no, they won't.

00:16:45.989 --> 00:16:46.780
What do we call it?

00:16:46.780 --> 00:16:49.750
Synthesizing DNA, yes,
because that's a lot harder.

00:16:49.750 --> 00:16:52.170
But eventually, information
will-- technology

00:16:52.170 --> 00:16:55.010
will develop to a point where
we can do that exponentially

00:16:55.010 --> 00:16:57.330
faster and cheaper as well.

00:16:57.330 --> 00:17:01.190
So what happens, what's
capitalism doing?

00:17:01.190 --> 00:17:04.630
How is it changing to defend
itself against these problems?

00:17:04.630 --> 00:17:07.310
Well, you're sitting in one
of the defense mechanisms.

00:17:07.310 --> 00:17:10.099
The evolution of the
large technology company,

00:17:10.099 --> 00:17:12.500
which exists one way
or another-- I'll

00:17:12.500 --> 00:17:16.530
put it simply like this--
to create a barrier

00:17:16.530 --> 00:17:20.000
around some information products
whereby that price does not

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:21.250
fall to zero.

00:17:21.250 --> 00:17:23.670
Now your one is quite
an interesting one.

00:17:23.670 --> 00:17:26.760
We can talk about the
interesting way it has adapted.

00:17:26.760 --> 00:17:28.460
I'm a fan of it.

00:17:28.460 --> 00:17:30.010
But let me give
you a good example.

00:17:30.010 --> 00:17:33.440
99p a track on iTunes.

00:17:33.440 --> 00:17:34.780
What determines that price?

00:17:34.780 --> 00:17:35.430
Supply?

00:17:35.430 --> 00:17:35.670
No.

00:17:35.670 --> 00:17:36.630
The supply is infinite.

00:17:36.630 --> 00:17:37.210
Demand?

00:17:37.210 --> 00:17:37.710
No.

00:17:37.710 --> 00:17:40.050
The demand might be
infinite, actually.

00:17:40.050 --> 00:17:41.470
We don't care what
the demand is.

00:17:41.470 --> 00:17:42.050
Quality?

00:17:42.050 --> 00:17:42.590
No.

00:17:42.590 --> 00:17:44.820
The same track by some
bog standard group

00:17:44.820 --> 00:17:48.920
is the same as a classic--
rock classic, 99p.

00:17:48.920 --> 00:17:50.720
It's determined by
the fact that Apple

00:17:50.720 --> 00:17:53.450
has a 95% share at
the time I start

00:17:53.450 --> 00:17:57.100
writing this book of
online digital music, that

00:17:57.100 --> 00:17:58.360
which is paid for.

00:17:58.360 --> 00:17:59.860
They can dictate the price.

00:17:59.860 --> 00:18:01.650
That's the defense mechanism.

00:18:01.650 --> 00:18:03.440
Of course, then you
create technologies

00:18:03.440 --> 00:18:05.130
that you have to use.

00:18:05.130 --> 00:18:07.910
It's easier to use
certain technologies that

00:18:07.910 --> 00:18:10.410
help you maintain that price.

00:18:10.410 --> 00:18:12.800
Now economics says
that the moment that

00:18:12.800 --> 00:18:16.240
is-- the moment that
monopoly is subjected

00:18:16.240 --> 00:18:18.950
to effective competition,
price should fall.

00:18:18.950 --> 00:18:21.000
And there's a website
called Information

00:18:21.000 --> 00:18:24.260
is Beautiful who have logged
the impact of competition.

00:18:24.260 --> 00:18:27.790
Because right now, to make
the minimum wage in the USA,

00:18:27.790 --> 00:18:30.610
a solo artist signed
to a record label

00:18:30.610 --> 00:18:35.900
will have to get 1,500 plays
on iTunes of a single track

00:18:35.900 --> 00:18:37.780
to make the minimum wage.

00:18:37.780 --> 00:18:40.890
On Spotify, it's 1.1 million.

00:18:40.890 --> 00:18:43.710
So the price-- the
impact of competition

00:18:43.710 --> 00:18:46.670
has collapsed-- tell me what
power of 10 that is-- it's

00:18:46.670 --> 00:18:48.560
collapsed the price.

00:18:48.560 --> 00:18:49.610
Right.

00:18:49.610 --> 00:18:54.240
Now to cut to the
chase, there's that.

00:18:54.240 --> 00:18:56.080
There's the tech monopolies.

00:18:56.080 --> 00:19:00.310
There is the fact that
we've actually begun to,

00:19:00.310 --> 00:19:05.780
as well, as human beings, I
would argue, live and create

00:19:05.780 --> 00:19:10.650
value and create our own social
image much more outside work

00:19:10.650 --> 00:19:12.136
than my dad's generation did.

00:19:12.136 --> 00:19:13.760
You all know that
workers for 200 years

00:19:13.760 --> 00:19:16.860
thought of themselves as kind
of communities and factories.

00:19:16.860 --> 00:19:19.090
Now through network
technology, we

00:19:19.090 --> 00:19:24.330
create several personalities,
and we live in networks.

00:19:24.330 --> 00:19:26.140
We live far more in networks.

00:19:26.140 --> 00:19:29.460
We are leaky in the terms
of our personalities,

00:19:29.460 --> 00:19:33.820
ourselves in a way that
previous generations didn't do.

00:19:33.820 --> 00:19:36.500
And at the edges,
we are beginning

00:19:36.500 --> 00:19:40.060
to see new forms of
economic production.

00:19:40.060 --> 00:19:44.030
So all the open source stuff
is a new form of economic life.

00:19:44.030 --> 00:19:47.700
It doesn't map onto the state,
the market, the public library.

00:19:47.700 --> 00:19:49.450
It's different.

00:19:49.450 --> 00:19:52.220
And I argue that
we might therefore

00:19:52.220 --> 00:19:54.760
be in the beginning
of a long transition

00:19:54.760 --> 00:19:58.990
whereby the state which we know,
which provides maybe 30% to 40%

00:19:58.990 --> 00:20:02.740
of GDP through providing
essential services,

00:20:02.740 --> 00:20:06.000
the private sector, which has
provided the rest, and then

00:20:06.000 --> 00:20:08.890
this new non-market,
difficult to price,

00:20:08.890 --> 00:20:12.920
free stuff and voluntary
incorporation sector

00:20:12.920 --> 00:20:14.490
is growing up alongside it.

00:20:14.490 --> 00:20:15.580
What's the problem?

00:20:15.580 --> 00:20:19.140
What's the problem for me, if
you use Ruby on Rails or PHP

00:20:19.140 --> 00:20:20.900
or whatever, it's not
a problem for you.

00:20:20.900 --> 00:20:24.270
Problem for me as an economist
is, how do I value it?

00:20:24.270 --> 00:20:26.570
There's a brilliant
tool called CATIA,

00:20:26.570 --> 00:20:29.650
which is used to virtually
manufacture aircraft.

00:20:29.650 --> 00:20:31.860
If you look at the small
print in Dessau-- Dessau

00:20:31.860 --> 00:20:33.910
systems owns this software.

00:20:33.910 --> 00:20:37.490
It's about 25,000
a head, a desk.

00:20:37.490 --> 00:20:39.197
It's a really top-end software.

00:20:39.197 --> 00:20:41.530
And then the small print of
their annual report it says,

00:20:41.530 --> 00:20:43.167
what's the main risk
to this company?

00:20:43.167 --> 00:20:44.750
It says, the main
risk to this company

00:20:44.750 --> 00:20:49.230
is that somebody works
out how to copy and paste

00:20:49.230 --> 00:20:52.500
the program CATIA 3.0.

00:20:52.500 --> 00:20:55.080
Because if they can do that,
then the value of this company

00:20:55.080 --> 00:20:58.040
falls from there to there.

00:20:58.040 --> 00:20:59.640
So economics just
doesn't know how

00:20:59.640 --> 00:21:04.200
to value or understand this
third post-capitalist sector.

00:21:04.200 --> 00:21:07.900
And the challenge for us is to
work out what to do about it,

00:21:07.900 --> 00:21:09.690
and whether or not
it's a good thing.

00:21:09.690 --> 00:21:12.060
I did a debate about this
book a couple of weeks

00:21:12.060 --> 00:21:15.130
ago with one of Jeremy
Corbyn's advisers.

00:21:15.130 --> 00:21:18.095
And a developer from
the open source world

00:21:18.095 --> 00:21:20.280
stood up-- it was in
St. Paul's Cathedral--

00:21:20.280 --> 00:21:25.630
and said, well, what should--
what should happen to me then?

00:21:25.630 --> 00:21:28.970
Should I be paid wages for
developing an open source

00:21:28.970 --> 00:21:29.670
product?

00:21:29.670 --> 00:21:31.810
And I said, no, because
that's postcapitalism.

00:21:31.810 --> 00:21:34.354
The point is, I write
my Wikipedia page.

00:21:34.354 --> 00:21:36.270
I'm going to make a
documentary and put it out

00:21:36.270 --> 00:21:40.230
for free, crowdfunded on
Indiegogo because I believe

00:21:40.230 --> 00:21:41.600
in this.

00:21:41.600 --> 00:21:45.070
I go to an organic farm
because I believe in it.

00:21:45.070 --> 00:21:47.630
And I want part of my
life to be non-capitalist.

00:21:47.630 --> 00:21:49.760
And this Corbyn
adviser said, no, no.

00:21:49.760 --> 00:21:51.120
You should be paid wages.

00:21:51.120 --> 00:21:54.480
And in other words, they
wanted to drag him back

00:21:54.480 --> 00:21:56.430
into the wage sector
because they just

00:21:56.430 --> 00:21:59.960
couldn't understand what
this new sector could become.

00:21:59.960 --> 00:22:03.338
I would like to expand that
new sector for this reason.

00:22:06.340 --> 00:22:12.900
I once interviewed Larry Page
and Sergey Brin before the IPO.

00:22:12.900 --> 00:22:16.840
And I said to them, what
is your remaining ambition?

00:22:16.840 --> 00:22:20.510
And like they said, I'd like
to design a machine that

00:22:20.510 --> 00:22:21.434
knows everything.

00:22:21.434 --> 00:22:22.850
At which point
there was this kind

00:22:22.850 --> 00:22:24.684
of massive jaw drop
among kind of all people

00:22:24.684 --> 00:22:26.683
who were sitting around,
because they all wanted

00:22:26.683 --> 00:22:28.490
to talk about computer stuff.

00:22:28.490 --> 00:22:31.190
I want to design a machine
that knows everything.

00:22:31.190 --> 00:22:34.660
Well, there's an
economist called

00:22:34.660 --> 00:22:37.606
Ken Arrow who was once the
guru of economics in the 1960s.

00:22:37.606 --> 00:22:39.230
He was one of the
first people to think

00:22:39.230 --> 00:22:40.840
about intellectual property.

00:22:40.840 --> 00:22:42.620
We used to think
intellectual property was

00:22:42.620 --> 00:22:45.300
like a public library.

00:22:45.300 --> 00:22:47.840
We used to think information
was like a public library.

00:22:47.840 --> 00:22:50.070
It was a public good
like a water system.

00:22:50.070 --> 00:22:52.340
You turn on and off,
[INAUDIBLE] it's just there.

00:22:52.340 --> 00:22:54.270
In the '60s we realized
it wasn't that,

00:22:54.270 --> 00:22:57.530
and we needed to economically
classify it and understand it.

00:22:57.530 --> 00:23:01.210
And Ken Arrow came up with one
of the neatest descriptions

00:23:01.210 --> 00:23:07.730
of what information property,
information-- owned information

00:23:07.730 --> 00:23:08.230
does.

00:23:08.230 --> 00:23:11.460
He says this.

00:23:11.460 --> 00:23:14.640
In a free market and
with private ownership,

00:23:14.640 --> 00:23:17.340
if entrepreneurs
produced patents

00:23:17.340 --> 00:23:22.230
and intellectual property, then
the aim is for it to be scarce.

00:23:22.230 --> 00:23:25.960
Therefore, in a free market
with private property,

00:23:25.960 --> 00:23:28.690
an intellectual
information economy

00:23:28.690 --> 00:23:33.960
will lead to the under-- the
systematic underutilization

00:23:33.960 --> 00:23:35.530
of information.

00:23:35.530 --> 00:23:37.720
Now I would like
to see a society

00:23:37.720 --> 00:23:40.860
where there is the
systematic full utilization

00:23:40.860 --> 00:23:41.750
of information.

00:23:41.750 --> 00:23:45.960
And therefore, what I
argue is that you probably

00:23:45.960 --> 00:23:50.980
can't have private property in
a free market in information.

00:23:50.980 --> 00:23:53.230
And it's the property bit
that I would like to attack.

00:23:53.230 --> 00:23:54.940
The market bit is good.

00:23:54.940 --> 00:23:56.650
It sorts out the information.

00:23:56.650 --> 00:23:58.000
It's the property bit.

00:23:58.000 --> 00:24:00.620
In other words, some
of it should be free.

00:24:00.620 --> 00:24:01.840
It wants to be free.

00:24:01.840 --> 00:24:02.800
It should be free.

00:24:02.800 --> 00:24:05.580
And so what I would
say to Larry Page now--

00:24:05.580 --> 00:24:07.330
I wish I'd thought
of it then-- but what

00:24:07.330 --> 00:24:10.120
I would say to him if I ever
met him again is you can't have

00:24:10.120 --> 00:24:12.050
that machine that
knows everything,

00:24:12.050 --> 00:24:14.380
that even this thing
that you guys work on,

00:24:14.380 --> 00:24:17.710
which is a machine that is
trying to know a heck of a lot,

00:24:17.710 --> 00:24:20.050
it can't know everything
for this reason.

00:24:20.050 --> 00:24:22.580
You can ask it any
question you want,

00:24:22.580 --> 00:24:25.140
but I can't ask it all
the questions I want,

00:24:25.140 --> 00:24:28.340
and therefore you don't
know what my questions are.

00:24:28.340 --> 00:24:30.200
I can only ask it
the dumb questions

00:24:30.200 --> 00:24:33.990
that I ask via the interface,
whereas if it was open source,

00:24:33.990 --> 00:24:36.010
we could all ask
it every question.

00:24:36.010 --> 00:24:42.370
And then your machine would
know everything far quicker

00:24:42.370 --> 00:24:44.930
than it's going to
at the current rate.

00:24:44.930 --> 00:24:47.590
I don't know what that means
for the commercial model,

00:24:47.590 --> 00:24:53.110
but it means that if we all
open sourced more stuff, then

00:24:53.110 --> 00:24:56.990
the leading edge of that which
is not ownable, not-- rather,

00:24:56.990 --> 00:25:00.900
that is ownable, that has
ultra value, that is innovative

00:25:00.900 --> 00:25:03.600
would be far more identifiable.

00:25:03.600 --> 00:25:07.920
And we'd all have a far
more equitable relationship

00:25:07.920 --> 00:25:09.910
with that which
should be shared,

