00:27:35.063 --> 00:27:36.220
which is about Karl Marx.

00:27:36.220 --> 00:27:37.650
And there's a
fascinating passage

00:27:37.650 --> 00:27:40.860
where you pick up on a
sort of lost document

00:27:40.860 --> 00:27:42.435
that Karl Marx
wrote in 1850 where

00:27:42.435 --> 00:27:43.875
he kind of predicted this.

00:27:43.875 --> 00:27:46.440
And there's a quote, which
I've picked out, which is,

00:27:46.440 --> 00:27:49.800
"capital collapses because it
cannot exist alongside shared

00:27:49.800 --> 00:27:50.300
knowledge."

00:27:50.300 --> 00:27:51.680
PAUL MASON: Yeah.

00:27:51.680 --> 00:27:53.760
So it's an amazing
document, "The Fragment--"

00:27:53.760 --> 00:27:55.630
it's called "The
Fragment on Machines."

00:27:55.630 --> 00:27:57.210
And it wasn't discovered by me.

00:27:57.210 --> 00:27:59.880
It was actually
really popularized

00:27:59.880 --> 00:28:02.760
by a guy called Antonio
Negri who is now well known

00:28:02.760 --> 00:28:05.920
for his work on the "Multitude"
and kind of far left

00:28:05.920 --> 00:28:08.910
of Italian-- he was
even more far left then.

00:28:08.910 --> 00:28:11.800
But Negri and the Italian
autonomous Marxists

00:28:11.800 --> 00:28:12.840
discovered this text.

00:28:12.840 --> 00:28:14.940
And what they
recognized is there's

00:28:14.940 --> 00:28:18.835
a completely other
collapsed story in there

00:28:18.835 --> 00:28:22.320
than there is in the normal
Marxism of "Das Kapital," which

00:28:22.320 --> 00:28:26.820
is all about the clash between
private ownership and equitable

00:28:26.820 --> 00:28:29.730
distribution, effectively.

00:28:29.730 --> 00:28:34.400
So in "The Fragment" he
basically says, look.

00:28:34.400 --> 00:28:37.370
What we're getting is
a kind of technology

00:28:37.370 --> 00:28:43.470
where all its effectiveness and
productivity derives from what

00:28:43.470 --> 00:28:45.630
he called social knowledge.

00:28:45.630 --> 00:28:48.610
That is, he'd
observe telegraphers.

00:28:48.610 --> 00:28:51.810
Telegraphers don't just work
with a kind of a switch.

00:28:51.810 --> 00:28:54.240
The machine is all
the telegraphers.

00:28:54.240 --> 00:28:56.340
In other words, it's
an early network.

00:28:56.340 --> 00:28:58.600
You could probably look
at early railway networks

00:28:58.600 --> 00:29:01.400
and identify some early
features of network

00:29:01.400 --> 00:29:03.380
rather than simply
hierarchy in them.

00:29:03.380 --> 00:29:05.640
But Marx is saying, what
this is going to lead to is

00:29:05.640 --> 00:29:09.920
when all the innovative
power of society

00:29:09.920 --> 00:29:12.860
is concentrated at
the level of ideas,

00:29:12.860 --> 00:29:14.660
then the private
property side of things

00:29:14.660 --> 00:29:15.790
is going to fall apart.

00:29:15.790 --> 00:29:19.230
And in an amazing leap-- he
calls it the general intellect.

00:29:19.230 --> 00:29:20.910
When there is a
general intellect,

00:29:20.910 --> 00:29:22.710
you can't have private property.

00:29:22.710 --> 00:29:25.700
But in an amazing leap, he then
does this thought experiment.

00:29:25.700 --> 00:29:26.560
He says, right.

00:29:26.560 --> 00:29:29.430
What would the ideal
machine be for capitalism?

00:29:29.430 --> 00:29:32.270
And he says, it would be a
machine that costs nothing

00:29:32.270 --> 00:29:35.340
to make and lasts forever.

00:29:35.340 --> 00:29:38.690
Because he says then,
then everything it does

00:29:38.690 --> 00:29:40.020
is beneficial.

00:29:40.020 --> 00:29:42.945
And everything it does draws
down to social knowledge.

00:29:42.945 --> 00:29:44.590
And it costs nothing to do.

00:29:44.590 --> 00:29:48.710
I mean, in other words, I think
software is a machine that

00:29:48.710 --> 00:29:52.300
costs nothing to reproduce
and would last forever

00:29:52.300 --> 00:29:53.270
if you wanted it to.

00:29:53.270 --> 00:29:55.120
It only becomes
obsolete-- it could

00:29:55.120 --> 00:29:57.590
last-- I'm sure that there's
a version of Windows 3

00:29:57.590 --> 00:30:00.650
sitting on a crappy old
laptop in my loft somewhere.

00:30:00.650 --> 00:30:03.120
If I fired it up-- I've got
a Mac that I can fire up

00:30:03.120 --> 00:30:04.565
and it's still got-- from 1984.

00:30:04.565 --> 00:30:06.120
It still works.

00:30:06.120 --> 00:30:07.790
So it's kind of--
it's the idea--

00:30:07.790 --> 00:30:12.370
and the problem is because he
wrote it at 4:00 AM in 1858,

00:30:12.370 --> 00:30:14.300
and then he never published it.

00:30:14.300 --> 00:30:17.360
And therefore, everybody
forget about it.

00:30:17.360 --> 00:30:19.830
But it's a fascinating
sort of insight

00:30:19.830 --> 00:30:21.677
into some of the
problems we are facing.

