down the [INAUDIBLE].

00:41:06.440 --> 00:41:08.480
PAUL MASON: Yeah, they can--
as a monopoly on violence

00:41:08.480 --> 00:41:08.980
everywhere.

00:41:08.980 --> 00:41:12.570
But I've seen it in my
professional career.

00:41:12.570 --> 00:41:15.990
Large masses of people use
technology to overcome that.

00:41:15.990 --> 00:41:18.310
Even now, the people
who are the most

00:41:18.310 --> 00:41:20.140
expert in the
Egyptian revolution

00:41:20.140 --> 00:41:22.190
will tell you that
it's not over.

00:41:22.190 --> 00:41:24.075
That even now when
you think it's over,

00:41:24.075 --> 00:41:25.920
over, over, it's not.

00:41:25.920 --> 00:41:27.110
The networks are alive.

00:41:27.110 --> 00:41:30.100
The ideas-- this is what the
great thing about infotech

00:41:30.100 --> 00:41:32.690
is, that in the
information world--

00:41:32.690 --> 00:41:34.160
you'll know this
from your work--

00:41:34.160 --> 00:41:37.460
no active imagination is
wasted because you can always

00:41:37.460 --> 00:41:39.810
record it and use it later.

00:41:39.810 --> 00:41:43.620
In the world of analog, then
kind of it's about spontaneity

00:41:43.620 --> 00:41:45.300
and the moment's gone.

00:41:45.300 --> 00:41:50.400
And so I think a lot of people
react to state crackdowns--

00:41:50.400 --> 00:41:51.350
like Syria.

00:41:51.350 --> 00:41:53.735
You could imagine, we
should be creating now

00:41:53.735 --> 00:41:55.956
a virtual Syrian university.

00:41:55.956 --> 00:41:58.330
In fact, you guys could do it
with your corporate weight,

00:41:58.330 --> 00:41:59.430
your Facebook, et cetera.

00:41:59.430 --> 00:42:02.610
Virtual Syrian university
that when it's over,

00:42:02.610 --> 00:42:05.440
just basically move
from the digital space

00:42:05.440 --> 00:42:08.190
to the analog space,
lands like a spaceship,

00:42:08.190 --> 00:42:10.360
and it can start
working immediately.

00:42:10.360 --> 00:42:12.610
We couldn't do things
like that 20 years ago.

00:42:17.110 --> 00:42:19.110
AUDIENCE: I was wondering
what your thoughts are

00:42:19.110 --> 00:42:21.296
on GMI, or basic income.

00:42:21.296 --> 00:42:22.004
PAUL MASON: Yeah.

00:42:22.004 --> 00:42:24.385
Well, I'm in favor of it.

00:42:24.385 --> 00:42:27.000
Universal basic
income, or the state

00:42:27.000 --> 00:42:29.400
as the employer
of last resort is

00:42:29.400 --> 00:42:31.440
the quick and dirty
or slow and dirty,

00:42:31.440 --> 00:42:34.850
but still nevertheless short
term answer to this problem of,

00:42:34.850 --> 00:42:36.140
how do we rapidly automate?

00:42:36.140 --> 00:42:40.510
I see it as a one-off subsidy
for rapidly automating

00:42:40.510 --> 00:42:41.100
the world.

00:42:41.100 --> 00:42:42.170
But of course, who pays?

00:42:42.170 --> 00:42:43.605
It's the taxpayer.

00:42:43.605 --> 00:42:45.480
I've done a back-of-the-envelope
calculation,

00:42:45.480 --> 00:42:49.710
that to pay everybody the
same as the state pension here

00:42:49.710 --> 00:42:51.922
as of right, no means
testing whatsoever,

00:42:51.922 --> 00:42:53.630
you get it whether
you're at work or not,

00:42:53.630 --> 00:42:56.990
six grand would double
the welfare bill.

00:42:56.990 --> 00:43:02.750
But some of the right wing
proponents of the basic income

00:43:02.750 --> 00:43:06.060
have kind of grasped some
of the economies of scale

00:43:06.060 --> 00:43:07.530
that you could do via that.

00:43:07.530 --> 00:43:13.076
That is, actually
for example, you're

00:43:13.076 --> 00:43:14.200
going to means test people.

00:43:14.200 --> 00:43:17.470
But lots of diseases
are to do with poverty.

00:43:17.470 --> 00:43:18.417
Lots of disease.

00:43:18.417 --> 00:43:19.750
And you could basically say, OK.

00:43:19.750 --> 00:43:22.800
Well, what do we save
from that for the taxpayer

00:43:22.800 --> 00:43:27.560
by managing diseases of poverty
and mental illness, type 2

00:43:27.560 --> 00:43:29.080
diabetes, et cetera.

00:43:29.080 --> 00:43:31.740
Stress, hypertension in
oppressed communities

00:43:31.740 --> 00:43:32.790
is very high.

00:43:32.790 --> 00:43:35.360
So if you could just take some
of the stress away from them

00:43:35.360 --> 00:43:38.370
by making them not have to worry
about where their money comes

00:43:38.370 --> 00:43:40.600
from, you could probably
save some of what

00:43:40.600 --> 00:43:43.250
it costs society that way.

00:43:43.250 --> 00:43:43.750
But look.

00:43:43.750 --> 00:43:46.220
You know, it's not-- everybody
knows about the basic income

00:43:46.220 --> 00:43:47.790
proposal, and there's a
right wing and left wing

00:43:47.790 --> 00:43:48.373
version of it.

00:43:48.373 --> 00:43:50.480
What is amazing is no
serious politicians

00:43:50.480 --> 00:43:52.135
are prepared to [INAUDIBLE].

00:43:52.135 --> 00:43:54.054
AUDIENCE: I have a
question on [INAUDIBLE].

00:43:54.054 --> 00:43:56.995
So you talked a lot about
the copying being free,

00:43:56.995 --> 00:43:57.495
which it is.

00:43:57.495 --> 00:44:00.072
But the first copy's
