00:44:00.072 --> 00:44:02.377
And you haven't really
said, how do you

00:44:02.377 --> 00:44:05.847
motivate excellent creation.

00:44:05.847 --> 00:44:06.680
PAUL MASON: Exactly.

00:44:06.680 --> 00:44:09.820
And I think the--
so my answer to that

00:44:09.820 --> 00:44:14.240
is that those of us who create
intellectual products only

00:44:14.240 --> 00:44:17.080
have to be really-- have to
really get it into our heads

00:44:17.080 --> 00:44:18.450
why we're doing it.

00:44:18.450 --> 00:44:19.730
So I've written this book.

00:44:19.730 --> 00:44:22.284
It goes out as an
analog copy like this.

00:44:22.284 --> 00:44:24.200
And I'm absolutely certain
there's a PDF of it

00:44:24.200 --> 00:44:25.770
somewhere on BitTorrent.

00:44:25.770 --> 00:44:28.070
But why do I want to do that?

00:44:28.070 --> 00:44:32.150
Because ultimately, I want to
make a statement to the world--

00:44:32.150 --> 00:44:36.160
and most authors will tell
you that hours versus income

00:44:36.160 --> 00:44:41.970
is minimum wage across lots
of branches of writing.

00:44:41.970 --> 00:44:44.800
But I know that as an
intellectual product,

00:44:44.800 --> 00:44:47.960
as an ebook, it is either
copyable or very easily-- so

00:44:47.960 --> 00:44:48.710
what do I do?

00:44:48.710 --> 00:44:49.270
What do I do?

00:44:49.270 --> 00:44:52.190
Where does somebody like
me make higher value work?

00:44:52.190 --> 00:44:54.300
They make it in corporate
speaking engagements.

00:44:54.300 --> 00:44:58.775
They make it in
advice, in consultancy.

00:44:58.775 --> 00:44:59.805
That's what's normal.

00:44:59.805 --> 00:45:01.430
Let me put it this way.

00:45:01.430 --> 00:45:04.010
Certain key artists
don't really care about--

00:45:04.010 --> 00:45:04.730
[LAUGHTER]

00:45:04.730 --> 00:45:06.680
--about whether their
work is pirated.

00:45:06.680 --> 00:45:09.499
Because Glastonbury
sells out in three hours.

00:45:09.499 --> 00:45:11.290
And in other words,
you move to the analog.

00:45:11.290 --> 00:45:13.670
So as creators of
intellectual property,

00:45:13.670 --> 00:45:15.720
we have to really
ask ourselves, where

00:45:15.720 --> 00:45:17.610
is the reward going to be?

00:45:17.610 --> 00:45:20.530
Now Hollywood has an answer
to this called lawyers.

00:45:20.530 --> 00:45:24.060
They would like the copyright
on James Bond's "Diamonds

00:45:24.060 --> 00:45:26.910
are Forever" to be still in
existence when the world is

00:45:26.910 --> 00:45:28.690
atomized and become dust.

00:45:28.690 --> 00:45:30.290
It matters to them.

00:45:30.290 --> 00:45:34.080
Their contracts say all time
and forever in the universe

00:45:34.080 --> 00:45:36.010
is the copyright.

00:45:36.010 --> 00:45:41.640
So what you can do is you can
record quicker and spikier

00:45:41.640 --> 00:45:43.480
the creation.

00:45:43.480 --> 00:45:45.800
I don't think The Beatles
wrote their music so it could

00:45:45.800 --> 00:45:48.500
be still in copyright in 2050.

00:45:48.500 --> 00:45:51.980
I think they wrote it to
meet attractive members

00:45:51.980 --> 00:45:54.421
of the opposite
sex and smoke dope.

00:45:54.421 --> 00:45:55.315
[LAUGHTER]

00:45:55.315 --> 00:45:57.124
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
this makes sense.

