00:46:07.430 --> 00:46:08.565
costs billions.

00:46:08.565 --> 00:46:11.660
And a lot of that work it
hard work and not particularly

00:46:11.660 --> 00:46:12.826
exciting and not fulfilling.

00:46:12.826 --> 00:46:14.360
The reason you're
doing it is clear.

00:46:14.360 --> 00:46:16.282
You want to save lives
in a perfect setting.

00:46:16.282 --> 00:46:18.840
But it's still
expensive, and you still

00:46:18.840 --> 00:46:20.039
have to reward that somehow.

00:46:20.039 --> 00:46:20.830
PAUL MASON: You do.

00:46:20.830 --> 00:46:25.430
And I would simply create a
copyright mentality that is

00:46:25.430 --> 00:46:27.917
shorter-- shorter and steeper.

00:46:27.917 --> 00:46:29.000
And I think that's doable.

00:46:29.000 --> 00:46:31.980
If you look at the different
copyrights and patent

00:46:31.980 --> 00:46:36.410
laws for IP, it goes from--
because you know the example

00:46:36.410 --> 00:46:37.640
of the generic drugs.

00:46:37.640 --> 00:46:39.030
So the HIV drugs.

00:46:39.030 --> 00:46:42.992
The Indian government basically
busted the world's pharma

00:46:42.992 --> 00:46:43.950
companies and said, no.

00:46:43.950 --> 00:46:45.470
You're not going
to do, no matter

00:46:45.470 --> 00:46:48.600
