00:54:20.300 --> 00:54:23.022
I say in the book that
a basic income is only

00:54:23.022 --> 00:54:23.980
a transitional measure.

00:54:23.980 --> 00:54:27.430
Because if you-- my ultimate
aim is to make as much stuff

00:54:27.430 --> 00:54:28.920
as possible abundant.

00:54:28.920 --> 00:54:31.330
And so basically,
to dissolve-- it's

00:54:31.330 --> 00:54:33.570
like taking the
complexities of the economy,

00:54:33.570 --> 00:54:36.180
drawing them on blotting paper,
and then dipping it in water.

00:54:36.180 --> 00:54:39.370
Basically, the complexities
disappear when stuff is free.

00:54:39.370 --> 00:54:42.930
You know, it's like if I take
your ball pen off your desk,

00:54:42.930 --> 00:54:45.950
you don't come running down to
reception saying, give it back.

00:54:45.950 --> 00:54:48.130
In a sense, once
stuff is abundant,

00:54:48.130 --> 00:54:49.940
you tend to stop
thinking about it.

00:54:49.940 --> 00:54:52.690
So that is the solution to that.

00:54:52.690 --> 00:54:57.010
But in the process, if
you've got a state, a market,

00:54:57.010 --> 00:55:02.030
and a non-market sector, then of
course-- think of it like this.

00:55:02.030 --> 00:55:05.210
The taxes from the market
sector pays for the state.

00:55:05.210 --> 00:55:07.460
But what comes from
the non-market sector?

00:55:07.460 --> 00:55:08.980
You know, the OECD
is very clear.

00:55:08.980 --> 00:55:11.320
This non-market sector
is big physically,

00:55:11.320 --> 00:55:13.030
but we just can't
value it economically,

00:55:13.030 --> 00:55:14.740
nor can we tax it.

00:55:14.740 --> 00:55:16.860
So you know, the
capitalist solution

00:55:16.860 --> 00:55:18.930
is to turn Wikipedia
into a corporation,

00:55:18.930 --> 00:55:21.845
make 27,000 people
micro employees,

00:55:21.845 --> 00:55:23.300
and get it to pay tax.

00:55:23.300 --> 00:55:24.550
That will be the solution.

00:55:24.550 --> 00:55:27.460
My solution will be to say
to understand that actually,

00:55:27.460 --> 00:55:29.620
what a product like
Wikipedia-- or we could use

00:55:29.620 --> 00:55:32.180
other examples-- is
actually creating

00:55:32.180 --> 00:55:34.670
a non-market value
through both the market

00:55:34.670 --> 00:55:35.695
sector and the state.

00:55:35.695 --> 00:55:37.570
It is like-- it's the
bit that you've already

00:55:37.570 --> 00:55:38.760
dipped in the water.

00:55:38.760 --> 00:55:40.700
We can't measure
it economically,

00:55:40.700 --> 00:55:42.750
so what we have to do is
to these other two bits,

00:55:42.750 --> 00:55:45.160
to really focus on them,
the state and the market

00:55:45.160 --> 00:55:46.340
and say, hold on a minute.

00:55:46.340 --> 00:55:48.730
They're going to be under
a long-term, strategic,

00:55:48.730 --> 00:55:51.740
century-long pressure
from this new sector,

00:55:51.740 --> 00:55:54.500
because it's going to-- it
looks like it's sucking value.

00:55:54.500 --> 00:55:58.570
I mean, the example I give as
well is the internet of things.

00:55:58.570 --> 00:56:00.570
There's a lot of hype
around internet of things.

00:56:00.570 --> 00:56:03.120
It's been described as a
$9 trillion opportunity.

00:56:03.120 --> 00:56:06.550
Yeah, it is, to take $9 trillion
of value out of the economy.

00:56:06.550 --> 00:56:09.150
Because all it will do
is make things cheaper.

00:56:09.150 --> 00:56:12.250
I can't-- yes, Cisco and whoever
makes switches will make a lot

00:56:12.250 --> 00:56:12.770
of money.

00:56:12.770 --> 00:56:15.650
Whoever installs all the
smart meters in people's homes

00:56:15.650 --> 00:56:16.570
make a lot of money.

00:56:16.570 --> 00:56:18.270
You guys have got
this app thing.

00:56:18.270 --> 00:56:22.520
I mean, you've got
this house thing.

00:56:22.520 --> 00:56:23.770
House energy thing.

00:56:23.770 --> 00:56:24.670
I can't remember
what it's called.

00:56:24.670 --> 00:56:25.000
MALE SPEAKER: Nest.

00:56:25.000 --> 00:56:25.958
PAUL MASON: Nest, yeah.

00:56:25.958 --> 00:56:29.760
I don't use it because
my house is analog.

00:56:29.760 --> 00:56:31.670
But, yeah, you'll make
money out of that.

00:56:31.670 --> 00:56:34.340
But ultimately,
what ILT will do is

00:56:34.340 --> 00:56:37.490
it will basically-- it will
basically make things cheaper,

00:56:37.490 --> 00:56:41.010
because it's going to
utilization of energy capacity,

00:56:41.010 --> 00:56:46.360
utilization of transport
capacity very, very efficient.

00:56:46.360 --> 00:56:51.670
So you have to ask the question,
how do we manage the transition

00:56:51.670 --> 00:56:54.830
to where this is a bigger
sector and a more virtuous

00:56:54.830 --> 00:56:58.360
relationship between what the
open source and free sector

00:56:58.360 --> 00:57:01.030
provides to the other
two sectors for free

00:57:01.030 --> 00:57:04.170
is utilized in an
efficient way, rather

00:57:04.170 --> 00:57:06.700
than being seen as
what I described it as,

00:57:06.700 --> 00:57:08.130
sucking value from it?

00:57:08.130 --> 00:57:11.526
Which is how economists would
try and-- they'd say, look.

00:57:11.526 --> 00:57:13.874
People now will say, you
know, Wikipedia's a $3 billion

00:57:13.874 --> 00:57:14.790
hole in the ad market.

00:57:14.790 --> 00:57:16.201
That's how people look at it.

00:57:16.201 --> 00:57:16.700
Well, no.

00:57:16.700 --> 00:57:19.660
To me, it's a great future
opportunity and virtuous thing.

00:57:19.660 --> 00:57:21.730
And I want to make
it better and more

00:57:21.730 --> 00:57:25.836
protected while controlling
the-- controlling

00:57:25.836 --> 00:57:27.460
the deflation of the
other two sectors.

00:57:27.460 --> 00:57:29.840
And for the left wingers
here, the traditional left,

00:57:29.840 --> 00:57:31.840
it's actually [INAUDIBLE]
as well, but deflation

00:57:31.840 --> 00:57:34.060
of the state sector as
well as the deflation

00:57:34.060 --> 00:57:35.390
of the market sector.

00:57:35.390 --> 00:57:37.860
But on that note-- and
the caveat that everything

00:57:37.860 --> 00:57:44.020
I say as a kind of, look, as
